    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Brasswork inlaid with silver or gold in knot patterns and mauresques. Azzimina was made in northern Italy, notably in Venice, and the Levant from the late 15th century to the 16th century. It is sometimes confused with damascening.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000011151/Fleming and Honour, Penguin Dictionary of the Decorative Arts (1989)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Koperwerk ingelegd met zilver en goud in knopenpatronen en moresken. Azzimina werd vanaf het eind van de 15de eeuw tot in de 16de eeuw vervaardigd in Noord-Italië, in het bijzonder Venetië, en in de Levant. Azzimina wordt soms verward met damasceen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>鑲上金或銀的紐結形花紋及摩爾式圖案的黃銅製品。生產於義大利北部，以威尼斯最為著名，並自15世紀後期至16世紀期間製於黎凡特地區(Levant)。有時會與金屬鑲嵌法(damascening)混淆。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
